{
  "text": "In a randomised controlled trial, it has been shown that lower body positive pressure, such as what occurs in the Trendelenburg positions, promoted restoration of normal haemodynamics. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Studies also suggest that oral hydration may be preventive against EAC and may also be used as an effective treatment for EAC. 43 44 A randomised controlled trial and two smaller trials suggest that skin surface cooling may act towards directing peripheral blood fl ow centrally and decreasing cardiovascular strain, thus treating EAC. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Finally, the results of a study of compression stockings in runners suggest that runners who are prone to OI after exercise may benefi t from wearing compression hose while running. [CITATION_6] Those prone to EAC may also potentially benefi t from taking H1 or H2 blocking medications, skin surface cooling along the course and ensuring adequate glucose levels during participation (table 5) .",
